    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_160541743" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/160541743" />
    <a title="Luke" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/1452964-luke"><img alt="Luke" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1219677952p2/1452964.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/160541743?book_show_action=true">Apr 12, 2011</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Luke" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Luke" href="/user/show/1452964-luke">Luke</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer160541743" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer10877957477363483366">Just a fantastic, heart-breaking, and inspiring book. I can&apos;t believe I hadn&apos;t read this book before now, but I&apos;m glad that I remedied the situation. This book was written by Pastor Richard Wurmbrand, a Romanian pastor who spent a total of 14 years in Communist prisons for daring to preach Christ under Communist rule. It is truly the work of a Spirit-filled believer who has had his faith tested and tried in the most oppressive conditions imaginable. Under conditions which would (and have) broken</span>
  <span id="freeText10877957477363483366" style="display:none">Just a fantastic, heart-breaking, and inspiring book. I can't believe I hadn't read this book before now, but I'm glad that I remedied the situation. This book was written by Pastor Richard Wurmbrand, a Romanian pastor who spent a total of 14 years in Communist prisons for daring to preach Christ under Communist rule. It is truly the work of a Spirit-filled believer who has had his faith tested and tried in the most oppressive conditions imaginable. Under conditions which would (and have) broken men for life, Pastor Wurmbrand recounts how the love of Christ and the Word of God shone more brightly, the darker their situation got. <br /><br />Similar to "The Hiding Place", what stands out for me is the thirst which these believers have for the Word and their Savior. It's hard for me to think of a more powerful witness to the truth of the Gospel than to read about the love which Wurmbrand and others bear for their tormentors. How even when they were being tortured endlessly, they cared more for the souls of their tormentors than for their own well-being. This unnatural love is simply impossible for the natural man.<br /><br />I knew about the Underground Church before reading this book, but it is heartening to hear stories about how it began and flourished under the Communists in Romania. I know that even now in 20+ places around the globe, fellow believers are suffering unimaginable deprivation for refusing to recant their belief in Christ. It truly serves to humble believers in the West who whine about "persecution" when we aren't allowed to say Merry Christmas during a school play. I recommend this book to any believer and also any non-believer who is interested to learn about the strength and grace of these saints in the face of savage and inhuman oppression. It is an uplifting story and one that helps to put your life into the proper perspective. The "prosperity gospel" is a shameful abomination on the face of Christendom and the fact that it hasn't been run out of town yet demonstrates that a lack of Biblical understanding coupled with pervasive materialism is more detrimental to the Church than unapologetic atheism.<br /><br />Thank you for taking the time to read my review.<br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="10877957477363483366" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


