<div id="review_3167684510" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3167684510" />
    <a title="Heather B" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/14830128-heather-b"><img alt="Heather B" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1579058316p2/14830128.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3167684510?book_show_action=true">Jan 30, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Heather B" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Heather B" href="/user/show/14830128-heather-b">Heather B</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was ok"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was ok</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3167684510" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer3000663442197225153">I gave this a two star because I really did read it and finish it. I read it in that time when being ‘crucified for Christ,’ was a big deal. I also read ‘The Heavenly Man’ during that time, and comparing the two, this one comes out less appreciated. I respect Richard Wormbrand’s passion for what he chose to do with his life, but he also comes off rather entitled and egotistical. At one point close to the end of the book he dis-es the younger generation for ‘confirming to the world’ too much whil</span>
  <span id="freeText3000663442197225153" style="display:none">I gave this a two star because I really did read it and finish it. I read it in that time when being ‘crucified for Christ,’ was a big deal. I also read ‘The Heavenly Man’ during that time, and comparing the two, this one comes out less appreciated. I respect Richard Wormbrand’s passion for what he chose to do with his life, but he also comes off rather entitled and egotistical. At one point close to the end of the book he dis-es the younger generation for ‘confirming to the world’ too much while he only reluctantly participated. His words and perspectives are cutting. I can’t help but feel that though he has done much to respect and follow Jesus, he forgot the tenderness. In contrast, ‘The Heavenly Man’ is enduring. The character in that book endured similar persecution, but maintains the undying love. He holds the truth and beliefs of Jesus with tenderness and helps others with that same tenderness. The cutting remarks that he makes is that the church in the west persecuted each other much worse than the physical torture in China, simply by using words to tear each other down. I find that synopsis much easier to take because it’s true, and is said with regret and with the passion to pray for change. <br />So, I give this book a two. I appreciate reading of those who placed their life on the line in order to teach others of Jesus, but if you can’t come through the torture maintaining the love, I feel like something need to change. Wormbrand, I’m pretty sure, had a severe case of PTSD, and he wasn’t able to find a way to healing. </span>
  <a data-text-id="3000663442197225153" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


