<span id="freeTextContainer16816171958615070523">This was a really interesting and eye opening read. It is an older book written in the 1960s. The style is different. Some parts may be tedious. Some parts seem irrevelant yet eerily familiar. <br/><br/>The author is the founder of Voice of the Martyrs. He is passionate about the Underground Church. This book wasn&apos;t so much about his many years of abuse and imprisonment, but a call to the Western church to wake up and help it&apos;s brothers and sisters and fight Communism.<br/><br/>So many times throughout the book I w</span>
  <span id="freeText16816171958615070523" style="display:none">This was a really interesting and eye opening read. It is an older book written in the 1960s. The style is different. Some parts may be tedious. Some parts seem irrevelant yet eerily familiar. <br /><br />The author is the founder of Voice of the Martyrs. He is passionate about the Underground Church. This book wasn't so much about his many years of abuse and imprisonment, but a call to the Western church to wake up and help it's brothers and sisters and fight Communism.<br /><br />So many times throughout the book I was wondering if we had jumped several decades ahead and he was writing about what is happening now in America.<br /><br />"The message I bring out from the Underground Church is: 'Don't abandon us! Don't forget us! Don't write us off!"<br /><br />"But I cannot remain silent. The West sleeps and has to be awakened!”</span>
